xwayland: survive libxcvt_gen_mode_info() returning NULL (fix deterministic crash)

SYMPTOM (two forms, same root cause)
  Older form: (EE) Segmentation fault at address 0x10, backtrace through
              ffi_call -> wl_display_dispatch -> xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt.
  Current form (after the partial fix that only added a NULL check in cvt.c):
              (EE) Fatal server error:
              (EE) Failed to allocate memory for list of RR modes
              kwin_wayland: Stopping Xwayland ... crashed 4 times over 10 minutes

ROOT CAUSE
  Xwayland builds its RandR mode list from the Wayland output geometry via
  libxcvt_gen_mode_info() (hw/xwayland/xwayland-cvt.c, called from
  output_get_rr_modes() in hw/xwayland/xwayland-output.c).

  Since libxcvt 0.1.3 (commits 410ef8f "Add bounds checking...", 23c30d4
  "Avoid potential division by zero", 049b79b "Add input validation...")
  libxcvt_gen_mode_info() now returns NULL for out-of-range input:
      hdisplay <= 0 || hdisplay > 1048576 ||
      vdisplay <= 0 || vdisplay > 1048576 ||
      vrefresh < 0  || vrefresh > 10000
  Older libxcvt (<= 0.1.2) never returned NULL for bad geometry, so Xwayland
  24.1 never handled it.

  apply_output_change() feeds xwl_output->{width,height,refresh} straight into
  output_get_rr_modes() on every wl_output/xdg_output "done" event. During
  early output setup, hotplug, or VRR / adaptive-sync mode-flapping, that
  geometry can be transiently 0 (e.g. xdg_output logical_size not yet received).
  libxcvt then returns NULL, and Xwayland either dereferenced it (SIGSEGV at
  0x10 = ->dot_clock) or, once cvt.c returns NULL, hit the FatalError() in
  output_get_rr_modes(). Either way the server aborts and KWin gives up after
  4 restarts.

FIX (two layers, both in Xwayland; no libxcvt change required)
  1) hw/xwayland/xwayland-cvt.c: xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt() returns Bool and
     xwayland_cvt() returns NULL on libxcvt failure instead of dereferencing a
     NULL pointer. (Prevents the SIGSEGV-at-0x10 form.)
  2) hw/xwayland/xwayland-output.c: output_get_rr_modes() now
       - clamps invalid primary geometry (width/height <= 0) to a 1024x768
         fallback and an out-of-range refresh to 60Hz, so the *actual* output
         mode can always be generated; and
       - treats the optional fake/emulated CVT modes as best-effort: if libxcvt
         rejects one, it is skipped rather than aborting the server.
     The FatalError() now only triggers on a genuine primary allocation
     failure, which is the original intent.

  Net effect: a transient bad output event degrades gracefully (a fallback mode
  is advertised) instead of killing Xwayland and the session.

Signed-off-by: ms178
--- a/hw/xwayland/xwayland-cvt.c
+++ b/hw/xwayland/xwayland-cvt.c
@@ -29,7 +29,7 @@
 
 #include "xwayland-cvt.h"
 
-static void
+static Bool
 xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt(xRRModeInfo *modeinfo,
                            int hdisplay, int vdisplay, float vrefresh,
                            Bool reduced, Bool interlaced)
@@ -39,6 +39,15 @@
     libxcvt_mode_info =
         libxcvt_gen_mode_info(hdisplay, vdisplay, vrefresh, reduced, interlaced);
 
+    /* libxcvt_gen_mode_info() returns NULL on allocation failure and, since
+     * libxcvt 0.1.3+ (input-validation commits 410ef8f/23c30d4/049b79b), also
+     * when the requested geometry/refresh is out of range (hdisplay/vdisplay
+     * <= 0 or > 1048576, vrefresh < 0 or > 10000). Xwayland used to dereference
+     * the result unconditionally -> SIGSEGV at 0x10 (->dot_clock). Fail
+     * gracefully and let the caller decide instead of crashing the server. */
+    if (!libxcvt_mode_info)
+        return FALSE;
+
     modeinfo->width      = libxcvt_mode_info->hdisplay;
     modeinfo->height     = libxcvt_mode_info->vdisplay;
     modeinfo->dotClock   = libxcvt_mode_info->dot_clock * 1000.0;
@@ -51,6 +60,8 @@
     modeinfo->modeFlags  = libxcvt_mode_info->mode_flags;
 
     free(libxcvt_mode_info);
+
+    return TRUE;
 }
 
 RRModePtr
